      "shell": "Maple",
      "description": "Blake Richardson's primary snare for studio and touring work has been a DW Collector's Series maple snare at the standard 14\" x 6.5\" configuration. The maple shell construction delivers a warm, full-bodied crack — distinct from the brighter attack of steel or aluminum alternatives — that sits well in BTBAM's dense production where the snare needs authority without being harsh.\n\nIn a band whose guitar arrangements cover death metal riffing, jazz voicings, and ambient textures within a single track, the snare must be versatile. The DW Collector's maple provides that versatility: tuned medium-high it delivers the cutting crack needed to drive blast beat passages; tuned medium it settles into the more restrained, groove-oriented sections of BTBAM's arrangements. Richardson's ghost note work — a critical element of his jazz-influenced technique — reads clearly through the maple's warm midrange, giving his dense hi-hat-and-ghost-note patterns the definition they require.\n\nThe 6.5\" depth adds body to each stroke, ensuring the snare doesn't disappear in the band's heaviest arrangements. Evans G2 Coated batter heads provide the two-ply control and slightly dampened sustain his technique demands, with a transparent snare-side head allowing full wire sensitivity for the delicate ghost note work that appears throughout BTBAM's catalog.\n\nRichardson has noted the importance of a snare that sounds musical rather than aggressive in isolation — a preference that reflects BTBAM's compositional approach, where even the most intense passages are arranged with jazz-musician's attention to tone.",
