      "title": "Blake Richardson's Approach: Metric Modulation and Progressive Composition",
      "content": "Blake Richardson's drumming philosophy is built on one foundational principle: the drums are a compositional instrument, not an accompaniment instrument. In Between the Buried and Me's music — which spans death metal, jazz, prog rock, ambient, and baroque-influenced passages within single extended tracks — Richardson's role is not simply to keep time but to be one of the primary musical voices shaping the arrangement. This distinction is what separates him from technically proficient drummers who lack his musical depth.\n\n**Metric Modulation:**\nRichardson's most discussed technical skill is his facility with metric modulation — the technique of shifting tempo perception by reinterpreting note values within an existing rhythmic framework. Where a simple tempo change involves moving from one BPM to another, metric modulation creates a perceptual shift while maintaining a consistent underlying pulse. In BTBAM's arrangements, these modulations allow the band to move between radically different feels — a 6/8 triplet groove resolving into a driving 4/4 at a new tempo, or a polyrhythmic 5 against 4 pattern shifting the bar length — without losing the listener's sense of forward momentum. See [polyrhythm and metric modulation technique at MetalForge](/technique/polyrhythm) for a deeper breakdown of these concepts.\n\n**Ghost Notes and Jazz Influence:**\nRichardson's hi-hat and ghost note work draws directly from jazz drumming. Dense sixteenth-note ghost note patterns between backbeats, frequent use of the hi-hat foot as an independent voice, and the use of dynamics within a single bar (louder accents, quieter ghost strokes, rim shots for accent) create a rhythmic texture that is far more sophisticated than most metal drumming. This jazz influence is audible throughout *Colors* and *The Parallax II* — in the way Richardson's hands create countermelodies against the guitars rather than simply reinforcing the rhythmic layer.\n\n**Genre Transitions:**\nBTBAM songs change genre multiple times within a single track. Richardson manages these transitions by anticipating the change in feel — he begins shifting the rhythmic texture one or two bars before the compositional transition, using fill patterns, cymbal choices, and dynamic shifts to prepare the listener rather than simply executing an abrupt change. This anticipatory approach is one of the most musically sophisticated aspects of his playing and one that requires deep knowledge of the arrangements he is executing.\n\n**Compositional Double Bass:**\nRichardson uses double bass as a compositional tool rather than a default mode. He varies kick density — denser during high-intensity extreme metal passages, sparser during jazz and ambient sections — to follow the music's emotional arc. The DW 9002 provides the consistent platform his foot technique requires; the compositional intelligence that decides when to use it is the product of BTBAM's collaborative songwriting process.\n\nFor comparison with other drummers who occupy comparable progressive metal spaces, see [Travis Orbin at MetalForge](/drummer/travis-orbin) — Periphery's technical prog specialist — and the [Blackwater Park drum setup breakdown](/articles/blackwater-park-drum-setup) covering Martin Lopez's jazz-to-metal approach with Opeth.",
